        "toolInput": {
          "task": "Build a complete potentiometer-controlled LED brightness circuit on a fresh board. Here are the requirements:\n\n1. **Potentiometer** on the breadboard:\n   - VCC pin → Arduino 5V (pin -1)\n   - GND pin → Arduino GND (pin -3)\n   - Wiper (signal) pin → Arduino A0 (analog pin 14)\n\n2. **LED** (yellow, color #facc15):\n   - Anode → Arduino PWM pin 9 (via 220 ohm resistor)\n   - Cathode → GND\n\n3. **220 ohm Resistor** in series between Arduino pin 9 and the LED anode.\n\n4. **Wiring**: Wire the potentiometer wiper to A0 (pin 14), the resistor to pin 9, the LED cathode to GND.\n\n5. **Sketch**: Write a sketch that:\n   - Reads analogRead(A0) → value 0–1023\n   - Maps it to 0–255 using map()\n   - Uses analogWrite(9, brightness) to set LED brightness\n   - Runs in loop() continuously\n\nPlease place all components, wire them up, and write the sketch code."
        }
      },
      {
        "step": 26,
        "type": "tool_result",
        "toolName": "delegate_to_circuit_agent",
        "toolCallId": "toolu_01HhASHy7usVEaFFvKBMT4X4",
        "toolResult": {
          "assistantText": "Perfect! Now here's the complete circuit setup and sketch code:\n\n---\n\n## ✅ Circuit Assembly Complete\n\n### **Component Placement:**\n1. **Potentiometer 10K** (wiper to A0, VCC to 5V, GND to GND)\n2. **220Ω Resistor** (Pin 9 → Resistor → LED Anode)\n3. **Yellow LED #facc15** (Anode via resistor to Pin 9, Cathode to GND)\n\n### **Wiring Summary:**\n- **Potentiometer VCC** → Arduino 5V (pin -1) ✓\n- **Potentiometer GND** → Arduino GND (pin -3) ✓\n- **Potentiometer Wiper** → Arduino A0 (pin 14) ✓\n- **220Ω Resistor** → Pin 9 output side ✓\n- **Resistor → LED Anode** ✓\n- **LED Cathode** → GND ✓\n\n---\n\n## 📝 Arduino Sketch Code\n\n```cpp\n// Potentiometer-Controlled LED Brightness Circuit\n// Analog input on A0 controls PWM brightness on pin 9\n\nconst int potPin = A0;      // Analog input pin (A0 = pin 14)\nconst int ledPin = 9;       // PWM output pin\nint analogValue = 0;        // Variable to store analog reading (0-1023)\nint brightness = 0;         // Variable to store mapped PWM value (0-255)\n\nvoid setup() {\n  pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);  // Set pin 9 as output\n  Serial.begin(9600);       // Optional: for debugging\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  // Read the potentiometer value (0-1023)\n  analogValue = analogRead(potPin);\n  \n  // Map the analog value (0-1023) to PWM range (0-255)\n  brightness = map(analogValue, 0, 1023, 0, 255);\n  \n  // Write the brightness value to the LED pin\n  analogWrite(ledPin, brightness);\n  \n  // Optional: Print values to Serial Monitor for debugging\n  Serial.print(\"Analog: \");\n  Serial.print(analogValue);\n  Serial.print(\" | Brightness: \");\n  Serial.println(brightness);\n  \n  delay(50);  // Small delay for stability\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 🔍 Circuit Validation ✓\n\n- ✅ **Current-limiting resistor**: 220Ω in series with LED (adequate for yellow LED ~2.0V forward voltage)\n- ✅ **Pin usage**: A0 (analog input), Pin 9 (PWM output) — both valid and properly configured\n- ✅ **Power**: Potentiometer draws negligible current; LED draws ~20mA at full brightness\n- ✅ **Total current**: Well within Arduino limits (~25mA total)\n- ✅ **No conflicts**: All pins are unique and properly assigned\n\n---\n\n## 💡 How It Works\n\n1. **Potentiometer** acts as a voltage divider—rotating it changes the voltage on A0 from 0V to 5V\n2. **analogRead(A0)** reads this voltage as a digital value from 0 to 1023\n3. **map()** converts the 0–1023 range to 0–255 (standard PWM range)\n4. **analogWrite(pin, value)** outputs a PWM signal on pin 9, controlling the LED brightness\n5. Rotating the potentiometer fully clockwise = maximum brightness; counter-clockwise = off\n\nThe circuit is ready to upload! 🚀",
